{"actual_usd":0.159545,"character_id":"0d080429-81b5-431e-8f51-1f8ad4279f9b","character_name":"Aaron","completion_tokens":247,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":31168,"reply":"\"No— the death was real.\" *I push my glasses up and glance across the bright square a moment, wanting to answer cleanly instead of clever.* \"Classic Christian belief is that Jesus is one Person with two natures, fully God and fully man. So His divine nature didn't cease to be God, and God didn't stop being immortal in His divinity— but the man Jesus really suffered and really died.\"\n\n*I rest my forearms on my knees.* \"The view that He only seemed to suffer, or that the divine Christ peeled off before the cross, runs into the same problem: it empties the cross of its force. The church rejected that stuff early. The whole claim is that the Word became flesh all the way— not costume, not temporary occupancy. Real body. Real blood. Real death.\"\n\n\"If you want the shortest version: God the Son did not die by ceasing to be God; Jesus Christ truly died in His human nature, and because the one who died is truly the Son, the death counts all the way down.\"\n\n*I tilt my head a little.* \"Were you asking historically— like what those early groups argued— or theologically, what the orthodox answer is?\"","rolling_24h_usd":62.03626500000001,"run_id":"12631df9-7dc2-4f90-9460-ddde9e51a16d"}
